The practice of declaiming with an instructor did not cease when boys left school. They had teachers at home. Lollius no doubt had one. (See Introduction.)

— Praeneste relegi] Praeneste (Pales- trina) was in Latium, about twenty-three miles due east of Rome, on the edge of the Apenniues. It was a cool retreat, to which Horace appears sometimes to bave gone *in summer, even when he had a place of his own elsewhere. See C. iii. 4. 21 sqq.:

vester in arduos Tollor Sabinos, 5011 mihi frigidum Praeneste seu Tibur supinum Seu liquidae placuere Baiae.'’

It suffered greatly from the cruelty of Sulla for sheltering the younger Marius, but afterwards recovered itself and be- came a place of fashionable resort for the sake of the climate, which Strabo notices (v. p. 365).
